  <mainDescription>Rules are illustrated in rule diagrams and they consist of rule elements. They are hierarchically integrated by&#xD;
connections, so there are special subsets for conditions, statements, keywords and connectors. Those are specialised sets&#xD;
of connectors (xor, or, and), keywords (if, then, else, check), conditions and statements. The last two concepts can have&#xD;
atomic entities. Keywords decide the further rule flow. &lt;br />&#xD;
Checks can be used to proof specific states during the rule flow. The rule concept is aligned to the business motivation&#xD;
model to implement the motivation, which follows some strategy. The implementation of processes according to the rule can&#xD;
be found in the statement element. When a statement is true, then the underlying process will be executed.&amp;nbsp;</mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The main objective of this model is to&amp;nbsp;provide constructs for Business Rules in order to describe the decision&#xD;
    rules.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
